</div><h2 id=3D"priming-sugar-by-the-numbers">Priming Sugar By the Numbers<=
/h2>
<p>Nope, we=E2=80=99re not talking about prime numbers. We=E2=80=99re much =
more interested in <em>priming numbers</em>=E2=80=94the formulas that let y=
ou create the perfect priming blend for your brew.</p>
<h3>Setting Your Target Carbonation</h3>
<p>Before you calculate the amount of sugar you=E2=80=99ll need to create a=
 priming solution for your brew, make sure you know:</p>
<ul>
<li>The residual carbonation present in your brew after a round of fermenta=
tion (determined by the temperature at which you ferment your brew).</li>
<li>The target carbonation for the beer style you=E2=80=99re making.</li>
</ul>
<p>This info is essential because <strong>Residual Carbonation Level + Prim=
ing Carbonation Levels =3D Target Carbonation Level</strong>.</p>
<p>Your best bet is to use a carbonation priming chart to <a href=3D"https:=
//byo.com/article/carbonation-homebrew-science/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"n=
oopener" data-lasso-id=3D"251662">help you estimate</a> the amount of carbo=
nation you=E2=80=99d like to add with your priming solution.</p>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> The chart we=E2=80=99ve shared also provides some=
 basic recommendations for priming five gallons of brew with dextrose or su=
crose at assorted temperatures, but for the nitty-gritty (and a deeper unde=
rstanding of the process), read on.</p>
