<h3>Using Corn Sugar</h3>
<p>The most popular priming sugar, standard corn sugar is roughly 9% water,=
 which means only 91% of its mass can be used in calculating the carbonatio=
n it will generate. This gives us the following formula:</p>
<p>C<sub>F</sub> + .5 x (.91D)/V<sub>B</sub> =3D C<sub>B</sub></p>
<p>Where:<br>
<strong>C<sub>F</sub></strong> is the level of CO<sub>2</sub> in your flat =
brew (in grams/litre), known as volumes or =E2=80=9Cvols=E2=80=9D in the Im=
perial system.</p>
<p><strong>D</strong> is the amount of corn sugar (in grams).</p>
<p><strong>V<sub>B</sub></strong> is the volume of your brew (in litres).</=
p>
<p><strong>C<sub>B</sub></strong> is the carbonation level of your finished=
 beer (in litres), known as volumes or =E2=80=9Cvols=E2=80=9D in the Imperi=
al system.</p>
<p><strong>EXAMPLE SOLUTION:</strong> Consulting your carbonation priming c=
hart, you=E2=80=99ll see an American ale fermented at 71=C2=B0 F (21.7=C2=
=B0 C) has a residual carbonation of .807 (1.58 g/l). You=E2=80=99ve set yo=
ur target carbonation at 2.6 volumes (5.1 g/l), which is within the range o=
f 2.2 to 3.0 for American ales. Let=E2=80=99s take a look at the formula us=
ing the standard 3/4 cup (113g) measurement of corn sugar.</p>
<p>1.58 + .5 (.91(113)/19) =3D 4.29 g/l, or 2.19 volumes.</p>
<p>That=E2=80=99s a bit low. Adjusting the amount of dextrose to 145g (5.1 =
oz.), we get:</p>
<p>1.58 + .5 (.91(145)/19) =3D 5.05 g/l, or 2.58 volumes.</p>
